        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062654"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Timothy W. Martin，</a></span>首尔； <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gordon-lubold" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gordon Lubold，</a></span>华盛顿</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 18 日晚上 7:15（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国官员称，一名美国士兵在韩国一侧巡视期间越过边境后被朝鲜当局拘留。</p><p>负责监督朝鲜半岛局势的驻韩美军发言人伊萨克·泰勒上校表示，这名美国军人当时正在朝鲜两国之间的联合安全区巡视，未经允许，故意越过军事分界线进入朝鲜。大约有28,500名美国军事人员驻扎在韩国。</p><p>美国官员称，这名士兵被确认为陆军一等兵特拉维斯·金，最近因不明原因在韩国被拘留。随后，他从轮换到的韩国部队被释放，预计将返回美国在他的家乡部队服役。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1068" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/867c108b-9cd5-4f9d-b318-b15cf01feec4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>根据金的服役记录，他是一名骑兵侦察兵，自 2021 年 1 月起一直在陆军服役，但没有服役。</p><p>泰勒上校说，美国认为他目前被朝鲜拘留。他补充说，以美国为首的联合国司令部正在与朝鲜对应部门联系，以“解决这一事件”。</p><p>白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔表示，白宫、国防部、国务院和联合国正在努力获取更多信息并解决这一问题。让-皮埃尔表示，拜登已获悉这一事件，美国官员已与朝鲜、韩国和瑞典的同行取得联系。</p><p>国防部长劳埃德·奥斯汀表示，正在努力通知该士兵的近亲。</p><p> “我们还有很多东西需要学习，”他在五角大楼的新闻发布会上说。 “这将在未来几天内发展。”</p><p>共同安全区位于朝韩两国之间的非军事区内，是韩国游客的热门旅游景点。这里是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officer-on-a-pink-phone-dials-down-north-korea-tensions-11558287392?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">朝鲜和韩国军队</a>沿着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/man-who-crossed-dmz-into-north-korea-is-a-previous-defector-11641212793?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">长约 150 英里、宽超过 2 英里的非军事</a>区唯一面对面的地方。在共同安全区，两个朝鲜被军事分界线从中间分开。</p><p> JSA 也是一处历史遗址，涉及朝鲜的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-says-north-koreas-kim-wants-to-meet-11561862697?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">高调会议</a>经常在此举行。 2019年，前总统唐纳德·特朗普在现场会见了朝鲜领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金正恩</a>，成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-north-korea-moment-started-with-a-tweet-ended-with-a-step-11561911990?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">第一位踏入朝鲜的在任美国总统</a>。最近的两次朝韩峰会也在那里举行。</p><p>朝鲜没有立即对美国人发表评论。关于释放该男子的任何谈判都将在美朝关系紧张的时刻进行，因为两国在没有外交的情况下<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">加强了军事力量的展示</a>。</p><p>东京和首尔官员表示，当地时间周三凌晨 3 点 30 分左右，朝鲜在其东海岸发射了两枚短程导弹，导弹飞行了约 350 英里，高度约 30 英里，然后落入朝鲜半岛之间的水域。朝鲜半岛和日本。平壤今年已进行了十几次武器试验。</p><p>美国和朝鲜已近四年没有举行正式裁军谈判。拜登政府一再努力与平壤接触，提出在任何地方、无先决条件进行会面。周二，朝鲜再次否认与美国的接触是徒劳的，并表示未来的政府很容易推翻任何承诺。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="444" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819180?width=700&amp;height=444" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">韩国士兵在非军事区巡逻，该区横跨朝鲜半岛，长约 150 英里，宽超过 2 英里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ahn Young-joon/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果这个人想要叛逃，金正恩可能会尝试在国内利用这一点作为针对美国的宣传，他将美国称为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-koreas-kim-jong-un-says-u-s-is-biggest-enemy-11610154003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">国家的“最大敌人</a>”。在朝鲜人民正面临粮食短缺以及经济受到制裁和Covid-19大流行打击之际，这种士气提振可能会有所帮助。如果美国人想离开，平壤可能会获得筹码或善意，通过谈判实现移交，而该政权无需付出任何代价。</p><p>为了确保 2018 年被朝鲜拘留的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-pyongyang-pompeo-expresses-hope-about-working-with-north-korea-1525848842?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">三名美国公民获释，</a>时任国务卿迈克·蓬佩奥 (Mike Pompeo) 访问了平壤。特朗普表示，金正恩释放三人的决定代表了“积极的善意姿态”。几周之内，特朗普和金正恩在新加坡首次会面。</p><p>自 2017 年被拘留在平壤并在返回美国后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/otto-warmbier-american-detainee-released-by-north-korea-has-died-1497905282" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">死亡的美国学生奥托·瓦姆比尔 (Otto Warmbier) 去世</a>后，美国人自 2017 年起被禁止前往朝鲜</p><p>JSA 内任何人越境的情况极为罕见。</p><p>根据结束 1950 年至 1953 年朝鲜战争武装冲突的近七年停战协定，联合国军司令部、韩国和朝鲜的士兵都被禁止跨越军事分界线接人。</p><p>几十年来，已有超过 33,000 名朝鲜人移居韩国，越过边境进入中国，然后通过第三国找到通道。但近年来，一些朝鲜人越过了戒备森严的非军事区，该区横跨朝鲜半岛。朝鲜一系列的边境违规行为引发了韩国对潜在脆弱性的批评。其中包括一名<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korea-says-individual-entered-north-korea-through-dmz-11641129034?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">离开朝鲜，后来又通过类似路线重新进入朝鲜的</a>男子。</p><p>疫情期间，JSA 的游览活动曾间歇性暂停，但去年又恢复了。通常情况下，JSA 允许大约 40 人参加团体旅游，目前每天仅限 1 人。从位于非军事区以南约 30 英里的首尔出发，乘坐巴士大约需要 1 小时才能到达那里。</p><p>在 JSA 的典型游览中，游客可以从天文台观察朝鲜，并参观“T-2”建筑（“T”代表临时建筑），其中包含一间会议室，与朝鲜举行高层会议。 T-2 大楼内没有军事分界线。</p><p>想要访问联合安全区的外国人必须在联合国司令部的严格监督下进行，包括至少在旅行日期前一周提交护照复印件。对于韩国国民和军事人员来说，一些限制更为宽松。</p><p> Lee Kyung-ryoon 说，对于参观共同安全区的游客来说，一个常见的问题是是否有可能进入朝鲜境内，尽管答案是否定的。Lee Kyung-ryoon 是一家总部位于首尔的公司，该公司已经进行了 20 年的非军事区旅游。李说，在他的访问中，没有人试图跨越军事分界线进入朝鲜。任何可疑的人都不允许上车。</p><p>这次旅行确实使游客更接近分界线。李说，冲过这条线并不困难。 “但没有人这样做，”他说。 “这是一个很大的风险。”</p><p>随着朝鲜减少在联合安全区的存在，边境地区的联合国军司令部士兵在疫情期间没有与朝鲜进行任何身体接触。自 2019 年与特朗普和金正恩交流以来，那里没有举行过任何高层政府会议。</p><p> 2018 年 9 月，朝韩两国关系升温并签署了《全面军事协议》，其中包括决定将共同安全区非军事化。该地区的哨所和枪支已被拆除。支持对朝鲜采取更强硬路线的保守派韩国总统尹锡烈去年上任后，首尔和平壤之间的紧张局势加剧。尹先生取代了左倾前任文在寅，文在寅优先考虑与金氏政权接触。</p><p>今年四月，朝鲜停止通过军事热线回应朝韩之间的通话，这是与韩国为数不多的直接沟通线路之一。通常，朝韩两国每天通话两次。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——常冈千惠子对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dasl Yoon（ <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com）</a> 、Timothy W. Martin（ <a href="mailto:Timothy.Martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Timothy.Martin@wsj.com</a> ）和 Gordon Lubold（ <a href="mailto:gordon.lubold@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gordon.lubold@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 23:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449<author><![CDATA[Dasl YoonTimothy W. MartinGordon Lubold]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特拉维斯·金</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The World Bakes Under Extreme Heat]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>变暖的海洋和热穹导致了有记录以来最热的夏季之一<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819299/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="周一，游客们聚集在罗马的一个喷泉周围。地中海地区的热浪本周将加剧。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>周一，游客们聚集在罗马的一个喷泉周围。地中海地区的热浪本周将加剧。盖亚·斯夸奇/彭博新闻<span>盖亚·斯夸奇/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001063900"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001063900"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alyssa-lukpat" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alyssa Lukpat</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joseph-deavila" itemprop="url" rel="author">Joseph De Avila</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-niiler" itemprop="url" rel="author">Eric Niiler</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-sylvers" itemprop="url" rel="author">Eric Sylvers</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/margherita-stancati" itemprop="url" rel="author">Margherita Stancati</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 4:28（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>致命的热浪正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/to-treat-extreme-heat-ice-packed-body-bags-and-wet-gowns-7c35c5c9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">颠覆美国、欧洲和亚洲大部分地区的日常生活</a>，海洋变暖和前所未有的湿度导致地球有记录以来最热的夏季之一。</p><p>气象学家表示，上个月是有记录以来最热的 6 月，如果 7 月创纪录的气温持续下去，2023 年可能会成为有史以来最热的一年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weeks-of-extreme-heat-strain-small-businesses-and-economy-add05101?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">给企业带来压力并威胁电网</a>。</p><p> AccuWeather 的高级气象学家布雷特·安德森 (Brett Anderson) 表示，有几个因素导致了今年夏天创纪录的高温。其中：异常温暖的海洋正在提高湿度水平；几个热穹在世界各地滞留热量的时间比平常更长；急流正在引发致命的风暴<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rescue-teams-work-to-reach-vermont-residents-amid-catastrophic-floods-65d9969d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，就像本月佛蒙特州发生的那样，风暴</a>移动缓慢。</p><p>炎热的海洋和反复出现<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ocean-warming-el-nino-noaa-ec2f124?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的厄尔尼诺现象</a>加剧了气候变化的影响，科学家称气候变化导致全球气温升高。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="474" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819303?width=700&amp;height=474" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，国家公园管理局护林员在加州死亡谷的数字温度显示器旁摆姿势。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：隆达·丘吉尔/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="438" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819311?width=700&amp;height=438" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">据 NOAA 称，最近几周佛罗里达州附近海域的温度超过 90 度，威胁着沿海的珊瑚礁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛丽亚·亚历杭德拉·卡多纳/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>世界气象组织咨询气候学家何塞·阿尔瓦罗·门德斯·皮姆包·阿尔维斯·席尔瓦在谈到极端热浪时说：“我们看到越来越多的极端事件，这是因为全球变暖。” “这些情况并非史无前例。但当它们发生时，它们的强度就会更高。”</p><p>据世界气象组织称，气候变化加剧了极端高温事件，自 20 世纪 80 年代以来，极端高温事件增加了六倍。气候变暖导致地表温度升高，使热浪持续时间更长、强度更大，并产生使热浪停滞在一处的天气条件。</p><p>据美国国家海洋和大气管理局称，在六月份厄尔尼诺现象加强之后，全球海洋温度连续第三个月创下历史新高。</p><p>过去几个夏天曾出现过带来酷热气温的高压热穹，但同时在陆地上出现四个热穹仍然令美国国家海洋和大气管理局 (NOAA) 工作的北卡罗来纳州立大学热带气候学家卡尔·施雷克 (Carl Schreck) 感到惊讶。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1670" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/e05688be-b98f-4698-aa16-6b815dd47b7f-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “我们在过去的几个夏天已经看到了这种情况，但当它真正出现时，它仍然是引人注目的，”施雷克说。</p><p>尽管如此，持续的热浪并没有阻止游客前往西班牙的海滩或参观华盛顿特区的地标建筑，有些人甚至在地球上最热的地方之一加利福尼亚州的死亡谷沐浴高温。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/290c4be8-c9ed-4afd-9309-ba895f015f7a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3>我们</h3><p>由于美国南部面临持续的高温，包括菲尼克斯在内的几个城市都打破了记录。德克萨斯州埃尔帕索周二连续第 33 天录得三位数气温，创纪录。尽管人们担心德克萨斯州的电网无法应对需求激增，但它们仍然保持稳定。</p><p>在北部，密歇根州、纽约州和佛蒙特州的部分地区今年夏天也打破了每日气温记录。</p><p>据 NOAA 称，最近几周佛罗里达州附近海域的温度超过 90 度，比正常水平高出几度。气温正威胁着沿海的珊瑚礁，并加剧了该州南部地区的炎热和潮湿。</p><h3>欧洲</h3><p>据世界气象组织称，欧洲正遭受持续热浪的烘烤，该热浪覆盖了地中海大部分地区。西班牙国家气象局警告气温将在 108 至 111 度之间，并向内陆和巴利阿里群岛发出警报。巴尔干部分地区也处于戒备状态。</p><p>预计意大利撒丁岛周二将接近该大陆历史最高水平。 2021 年 8 月，西西里岛创下了欧洲最高气温记录，达到 119.8 华氏度。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="925" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819312?width=1260&amp;height=925" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">意大利国家气象局发布该国南部地区极端高温警报。在北部，米兰的音乐会观众周二等待进入体育场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Piaggesi/ROPI/ZUMA Press </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819314?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲热浪期间，罗马的餐馆设置了喷雾风扇。预计到本周中旬欧洲的高温将会加剧。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Gaia Squarci/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819318?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">雅典卫城是雅典的主要旅游景点，即使在上周的热浪期间，雅典卫城也挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Angelos Tzortzinis/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p></p>撒丁岛桑卢里市长阿尔贝托·乌尔皮 (Alberto Urpi) 表示，当局已对该地区发布天气红色警报，建议人们从上午晚些时候到下午 6 点呆在室内。<p></p><p> “我们准备好了，”乌尔皮说。 “我们已经习惯了这些热浪，并且有时间组织我们的应对措施。”</p><p>由于天气炎热，当局在周五和周六的大部分时间里关闭了雅典卫城。预计希腊首都本周气温将保持在 97 度以上，周日最高温度接近 110 度。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0AD43FBB-1726-4D5C-9BCE-DF4AF94D3260&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fextreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">随着酷热席卷南欧，野火摧毁了雅典郊外的建筑物并烧毁了大片土地。非洲大陆的其他地区以及中国和美国都遭受了创纪录的气温打击。照片：Petros Giannakouris/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>亚洲</h3><p>另一场热浪同时席卷亚洲部分地区。据官方媒体报道，中国新疆西北部地区的一个村庄创下了 126 度的历史最高气温。</p><p>热浪期间，美国气候特使约翰·克里会见了包括北京最高外交政策特使王毅和国务院总理李强在内的中国官员，讨论如何加速脱碳和其他气候变化目标。中国和美国是世界上最大的温室气体排放国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819325?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国气候特使约翰·克里正在北京恢复有关减少温室气体排放的双边合作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：弗洛伦斯·洛-普尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819328?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上周，南京市民在防空洞避暑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/NurPhoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>世界气象组织的席尔瓦表示，目前该地区有高压系统滞留热空气。这些系统将在接下来的几天内保持不变。</p><p> “进展非常缓慢，但我们不会永远出现这种情况，”席尔瓦说。</p><p>写信给 Alyssa Lukpat（ <a href="mailto:alyssa.lukpat@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alyssa.lukpat@wsj.com</a> ）、Joseph De Avila（ <a href="mailto:joseph.deavila@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joseph.deavila@wsj.com</a> ）、Eric Niiler（ <a href="mailto:eric.niiler@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.niiler@wsj.com</a> ）、Eric Sylvers（ <a href="mailto:eric.sylvers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.sylvers@wsj.com</a> ）和 Margherita Stancati（ <a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 20:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d <author><![CDATA[Alyssa LukpatJoseph De AvilaEric NiilerEric SylversMargherita Stancati]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Lots of Tap Water Contains ‘Forever Chemicals.’ These Steps Reduce Your Risk.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>您无法完全避免有毒的 PFAS 化学物质，但您可以减少在家中的接触<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818375/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>图片由《华尔街日报》提供，ISTOCK<span>图片由《华尔街日报》提供，ISTOCK</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060204"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060204"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sumathi-reddy"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-733259/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sumathi-reddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">苏马蒂·雷迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 3:30（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfas-forever-chemicals-how-to-reduce-654cd05b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>有毒的“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-are-forever-chemicals-and-are-they-hazardous-to-your-health-11671563642?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">永久化学物质</a>”遍布你的家。但过滤水可以减少您的接触。</p><p>这些合成化学品也称为 PFAS， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-forever-chemicals-are-all-around-us-from-winter-coats-to-fast-food-wrappers-5a250b05?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">长期以来一直用于消费品中</a>，出现在从化妆品、牙线到地毯、雨衣和不粘锅的各种物品中。它们与包括癌症在内的许多健康问题有关。 PFAS 被称为“永远的化学物质”，因为它们需要很长时间才能分解，它分布广泛，但很难判断特定产品是否含有它们。</p><p>这些化学物质损害您健康的主要方式是您吃、喝或吸入它们。您的饮用水可能是家中最大的风险：根据美国地质调查局最近的一项研究， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nearly-half-of-u-s-tap-water-contains-forever-chemicals-study-says-985f6467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近一半的美国自来水</a>受到 PFAS 污染。</p><p>此外，地毯和室内装潢中的 PFAS 化学物质可能会脱落并被吸入。科罗拉多公共卫生学院安舒茨医学院公共卫生实践副院长 Ned Calonge 表示，有一些有限的证据表明，你可以通过穿衣服或接触含有 PFAS 的东西来吸收这些化学物质。</p><p> “你确实无法避免所有的接触，但你可以尝试避免一些常见的来源，”华盛顿特区非营利组织环境工作组的高级科学家塔莎·斯托伊伯说。</p><p>以下是有关您家中永久化学物质的信息以及如何降低风险。</p><h3>为什么这些化学物质有害？</h3><p> PFAS 是全氟烷基物质和多氟烷基物质的简写，是包含非常强的碳氟键的化学物质。这些化学物质具有特殊的性质，使其成为防水、防污渍和防油脂产品中受欢迎的成分。但这种结合也使得 PFAS 难以在环境和我们的体内分解，它们可以在其中保留多年。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818480?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据美国疾病控制与预防中心的数据，几乎每个人 <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2072821/" target="_blank" class="icon none">的血液中都含有一定水平的 PFAS</a> 。您可以询问您的医生关于测试您血液中 PFAS 水平的事宜。</p><p>杰基·古德里奇说，这些化学物质与多种健康问题有关，包括高胆固醇、某些类型的癌症和免疫反应下降。</p>密歇根大学环境健康科学研究副教授。<p></p><p>许多公司在 2000 年代初期停止使用其中两种最常见的化学品，即 PFOA 和 PFOS。其他人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/3m-to-stop-making-discontinue-use-of-forever-chemicals-11671541938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在逐步淘汰它们</a>。但科学家表示，一些公司正在使用可能具有类似有害特性的替代品。</p><h3>如何减少自来水中的 PFAS</h3><p>科学家表示，饮用水是 PFAS 暴露最普遍、最有害的来源之一。另一方面，疾病预防控制中心表示，在含有 PFAS 的水中淋浴或洗碗<a href="https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/pfas/health-effects/PFAS-exposure-and-your-body.html" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">不被认为是一种风险</a>。</p><p>今年早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/epa-proposes-regulations-for-forever-chemicals-in-drinking-water-b6963dfd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，美国环保署提议对公共饮用水中的某些 PFAS 化合物进行联邦限制</a>，该计划可能会在年底前最终确定。与此同时，专家表示您可以采取一些措施。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818447?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>联系当地的自来水公司，看看他们是否正在测量 PFAS 以及含量是多少，说</p>Aleksandra Szczuka，密歇根大学土木与环境工程助理教授。<p></p><p>使用常用的过滤器来过滤自来水。 <a href="https://www.ewg.org/research/getting-forever-chemicals-out-drinking-water-ewgs-guide-pfas-water-filters" target="_blank" class="icon none">EWG 最近的一项研究</a>评估了 10 种不同的过滤器，发现其中四种可以将水中的 PFAS 减少 100% 或接近 100%。其中包括 Clearly Filtered、Epic Water Filter、ZeroWater 和 Travel Berkey。</p><p>流行品牌 Brita 的六杯水罐可减少水中 66% 的 PFAS，而 PUR 的七杯水罐可减少 79% 的 PFAS。</p><p> Stoiber 说，从饮用水中去除 PFAS 的最有效方法是在家中安装反渗透系统。它们需要安装在水槽下方，您可以从 Home Depot 等商店购买。</p><p>她说，如果您从私人水井取水，您可能需要对其进行 PFAS 和其他污染物检测。您当地的水务部门可能会测试样品，或者您也可以找到一个独立的实验室。</p><h3>地毯和室内装潢怎么样？</h3><p>很难确定您的地毯或沙发是否含有 PFAS。一个可能的指标是产品何时以防污或防污的名义销售。您也可以致电或发送电子邮件给制造商询问。</p><p>包括<a href="https://corporate.homedepot.com/news/sustainability/phasing-out-products-containing-pfas#.XYD8x-3waIo.twitter" target="_blank" class="icon none">家得宝 (Home Depot)</a> 、 <a href="https://corporate.lowes.com/our-responsibilities/corporate-responsibility-reports-policies/lowes-safer-chemicals-policy" target="_blank" class="icon none">劳氏 (Lowe&#39;s</a> ) 和<a href="https://about.ikea.com/en/about-us/our-view-on/chemicals" target="_blank" class="icon none">宜家 (IKEA)</a>在内的一些公司已宣布将逐步淘汰地毯中的 PFAS。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818445?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>警惕声称产品不含某种特定 PFAS 化学物质（例如 PFOA）的营销。 “这意味着他们可能有不同的东西，”古德里奇说。</p><p>东北大学社会科学环境健康研究所所长 Phil Brown 表示，含有 PFAS 的地毯可能会不断脱落化学物质。科学家表示，目前尚不清楚这种脱落是否会随着时间的推移而减少或增加，或者在清洗或蒸汽清洁时会减少。</p><p>当然，您可以尝试将所有地毯更换为您确定不含 PFAS 的地毯。除此之外，你可以通过经常吸尘、拖地和除尘来减少家庭灰尘，位于加利福尼亚州伯克利的非营利组织绿色科学政策研究所表示。</p><p>尝试使用带有 HEPA 过滤器和机械动力头的真空吸尘器。您还可以在地毯上放置未经 PFAS 处理的游戏垫或地毯。</p><h3>其他需要检查的家居用品</h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818446?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>卡隆赫说，从受 PFAS 污染的水中捕获的鱼、用 PFAS 制成的牙线以及用含有 PFAS 的材料包装的食品都存在潜在风险。PFAS 因其耐油脂特性而常用于快餐容器。</p><p>很难知道产品是否含有 PFAS——许多产品都没有列出它们所含有的化学物质。 <a href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.estlett.1c00240" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021 年一项针对化妆品的研究</a>发现，即使在列出成分的产品中，即使未列出，也可能存在 PFAS。</p><p>许多不粘锅都是用 PFAS 制成的。卡隆赫说，如果表面仍然完好无损，化学物质就不会渗入你的食物中，但如果表面被划伤，你应该把它扔掉。环境工作组表示，即使不粘锅声称不含 PFAS，但用铸铁、玻璃、不锈钢或碳钢制成的锅具烹饪仍然更安全。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否正在采取任何措施来防止和尽量减少家中的有害化学物质？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>写信给Sumathi Reddy： <a href="mailto:Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 19:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfas-forever-chemicals-how-to-reduce-654cd05b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfas-forever-chemicals-how-to-reduce-654cd05b<author><![CDATA[Sumathi Reddy]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>化学品</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>产品/消费者安全</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>环境健康</category><category>癌症</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>自然资源稀缺</category><category>塑料污染</category><category>环境污染</category><category>水污染</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>产品</category><category>消费者安全</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>环境健康</category><category>癌症</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>自然资源稀缺</category><category>塑料污染</category><category>环境污染</category><category>水污染</category><category>化学品</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Europe Tries to Bridge Its Migration Divide]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>与突尼斯的移民协定是欧盟解决欧盟内部移民问题的最新举措<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818690/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="今年早些时候，突尼斯海岸警卫队试图阻止突尼斯斯法克斯附近的移民。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>今年早些时候，突尼斯海岸警卫队试图阻止突尼斯斯法克斯附近的移民。吉赫德·阿比德拉奥伊/路透社<span>吉赫德·阿比德拉奥伊/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060991"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060991"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span>（柏林）和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/margherita-stancati" itemprop="url" rel="author">玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂</a></span>（罗马）</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-tries-to-bridge-its-migration-divide-c8b1707c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>欧洲再次试图解决其最具分歧性的问题：移民。</p><p>经过多年的不和和法律斗争，欧盟正在制定一套严厉的新移民和庇护政策，包括采取措施缓解人们被拒之门外的情况。</p><p>周日，欧盟与突尼斯签署了一项协议，承诺提供经济援助和其他合作，以换取<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tunisian-president-targets-sub-saharan-african-migrants-mob-violence-follows-7a51495a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">突尼斯打击船只过境和遣返非法进入欧盟的突尼斯人的努力，</a>从而实现了其计划的第一部分。</p><p>自 Covid-19 大流行结束以来，进入欧洲和整个美洲的移民急剧增加，促使<strong>&nbsp;</strong>新举措收紧资金流入限制。拜登政府最近公布了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-new-immigration-system-works-after-title-42-ends-2fba7498?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对寻求庇护者的新限制</a>，宣布在前往美国途中途经另一个国家而未在美国寻求庇护的移民现在没有资格留在美国</p><p>欧洲的新举措是由意大利总理乔治亚·梅洛尼带头的，她的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-shipwreck-shakes-italys-anti-immigration-government-b35a6d81?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反移民立场</a>帮助她在去年的议会选举中大获全胜。</p><p>关于欧盟的计划是否会显着减少寻求非法进入欧洲的人数以及这些提议是否会得到全面实施，问题仍然存在。移民组织认为，6月份发生了一场悲剧，当时运送难民的过度拥挤的渔船沉没，据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/greece-migrant-ship-reveals-perilous-route-to-europe-260dd49b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">推测有数百名寻求庇护者在希腊海岸死亡，</a>之后，欧盟应该重新开放通往欧盟的安全合法通道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818707?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上个月，西西里岛兰佩杜萨岛移民接待设施内的移民。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：vincenzo livieri/EPA/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818692?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">这张从救援直升机拍摄的照片显示，上个月一艘渔船上的移民在希腊海岸沉没，据推测造成数百人死亡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：希腊海岸警卫队/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该计划仍面临波兰和匈牙利的反对，波兰和匈牙利此前曾就早些时候的移民提案起诉欧盟执行机构欧盟委员会。新计划还需要欧洲议会的支持，欧洲议会历来反对限制寻求庇护者权利的努力。</p><p>自<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/migrant-crisis-divides-europe-1441314666?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2015 年移民危机</a>以来，超过 100 万寻求庇护者（主要是叙利亚人）越过地中海逃入欧盟，移民问题在 27 个欧盟成员国中引发了激烈争论。这些斗争有时会导致其他政策的决策陷入瘫痪。</p><p> 2016年与土耳其达成一项协议，主要是向安卡拉支付费用以阻止叙利亚人进入欧盟。此后，欧盟成员国多次未能就控制非法移民的全面制度达成一致，同时也未能遵守为需要保护的难民提供庇护的国际义务。在过去的几年里，他们甚至没有尝试过。</p><p>动荡的移民政治并未显示出减弱的迹象。荷兰首相马克·吕特的政府最近在这个问题上失败了。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/immigration-backlashes-spread-around-the-world-142124bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反移民政党在包括奥地利、荷兰和西班牙在内的几个欧盟国家的民意调查中表现良好，</a>并且有能力在明年的欧洲议会选举中增加席位。</p><p>尽管如此，欧盟外交官上个月还是设法就解决这一问题的新方法达成了压倒性多数的协议，该方法成功地将梅洛尼的反移民重点与一些西欧国家首都长期以来要求欧盟共同承担寻求庇护者责任的要求结合起来。</p><p>该提案将允许各国预先筛查难民，并通过快速评估处理被认为不可能入境的人。它还将赋予每个成员国更多的权力来决定将失败的寻求庇护者送回何处。</p><p>作为交换<strong>，</strong>欧盟将寻求每年在欧盟范围内重新安置至少 30,000 名移民。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>如果一个国家拒绝接纳寻求庇护者，他们可以改为<strong>&nbsp;</strong>对于每一个不接受的人，他们将支付 20,000 欧元，相当于大约 22,500 美元。</p><p>在制定移民协议的同时，欧盟宣布欧盟委员会主席乌苏拉·冯德莱恩将与梅洛尼和吕特一起前往突尼斯就移民协议进行谈判。上周末，三人回归完成了交易。在六月， <strong>&nbsp;</strong>冯德莱恩提议设立一个超过 150 亿美元的基金，为突尼斯交易等外部合作伙伴提供资金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="486" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818702?width=700&amp;height=486" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，在与突尼斯达成协议后，荷兰首相马克·吕特、欧盟委员会主席乌苏拉·冯德莱恩、突尼斯总统凯斯·赛义德和意大利总理乔治亚·梅洛尼（左起）。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：突尼斯总统府/APA Images/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>梅洛尼是欧盟谈判的核心人物，他的右翼政府将解决移民问题作为外交政策的首要任务。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>以前的反移民拥护者往往会与布鲁塞尔发生争执。她通常与欧盟合作以实现她的目标。</p><p>联合国数据显示，今年迄今为止，已有超过 76,000 名移民通过海路抵达意大利，相当于登记在册的地中海抵达欧洲人数的 77%。</p><p>到达欧洲南部海岸的人数几乎是去年上半年的两倍，是自 2015 年移民危机以来的最高水平。</p><p>海上入境人数增加的一个重要原因是突尼斯的政治和经济动荡。该国独裁总统凯斯·赛义德带头发起了一场针对突尼斯撒哈拉以南非洲移民的运动，这加剧了突尼斯的不稳定。</p><p>周一，国际特赦组织批评了欧盟与突尼斯的协议，称该协议标志着“欧盟接受赛义德和突尼斯政府日益严厉的镇压行为”。国际特赦组织表示：“这使得欧盟成为不可避免的痛苦的同谋。”</p><p>梅洛尼没有表现出任何后悔的迹象。周日，她称赞突尼斯协议是欧洲和北非国家之间建立新型关系的“典范”。最近几周，她一直试图让波兰和匈牙利这两个有着相似右翼民族主义政治品牌的国家加入进来。</p><p>匈牙利总理欧尔班·维克托和波兰总理莫拉维茨基长期以来一直反对任何在整个欧洲大陆共享寻求庇护者的强制性机制，他们上个月参加了布鲁塞尔峰会，决心在没有他们支持的情况下谴责该协议及其达成方式。</p><p>莫拉维茨基在前往峰会的途中表示，宽松的移民政策导致欧洲街头流血。两人在长达数小时的深夜会谈中拒绝做出让步，并阻止了峰会关于移民问题的声明。</p><p>几天后，梅洛尼前往华沙与莫拉维茨基会谈。 “我们在这方面没有分歧，因为我们有相同的关键目标，这不是讨论如何处理欧洲的非法移民，而是如何阻止非法移民，”她在与莫拉维茨基的联合新闻发布会上表示。 “我们将继续共同努力，寻找对每个人都有效的解决方案。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="835" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818730?width=1260&amp;height=835" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在突尼斯斯法克斯，可以看到船只被突尼斯当局拦截的移民。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Hasan Mrad/IMAGESLIVE/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给劳伦斯·诺曼（ <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a> ）和玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂（ <a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-tries-to-bridge-its-migration-divide-c8b1707c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-tries-to-bridge-its-migration-divide-c8b1707c<author><![CDATA[Laurence NormanMargherita Stancati]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Despite Ukraine War, U.K. Set to Shrink Its Army]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新军事战略的重点是装备更好的部队和更多的弹药<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062646"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818395?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰陆军新兵与英国皇家海军陆战队成员一起参加训练课程。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亨利·尼科尔斯/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062646"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/max-colchester" itemprop="url" rel="author">马克斯·科尔切斯特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日上午 8:03 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-ukraine-war-u-k-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伦敦——随着俄罗斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的侵略</a>迫使欧洲最大的军费开支国和乌克兰的一个重要盟友重新审视其战略，英国将精简军队，并寻求建立一支装备更精良的部队，并表示可以更快地动员起来。</p><p>英国国防部周二公布的新战略计划旨在回应对英国军队的批评，分析人士称，在俄罗斯和乌克兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在欧洲打陆战</a>之际，英国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europes-defense-dilemma-to-buy-or-not-to-buy-american-1576c2f4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">军队缺乏有效的装备和弹药</a>。</p><p>自冷战结束以来，英国军队已从主要驻扎欧洲的常规军队转变为远征军，在阿富汗和伊拉克作战。现在， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-cant-afford-to-drop-the-ball-on-ukraine-u-k-foreign-secretary-says-95e6e5f8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">面对好战的俄罗斯</a>，它正试图两者兼顾，但预算紧张。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>英国表示，不会投资扩充军队，而是将重点放在采购技术上，“以确保我们的力量大于各部分之和”。该计划包括建立一支快速部署部队，可以赶往陷入困境的热点地区，以及一项确保更有效的武器采购系统的计划。政府还表示，在向乌克兰捐赠大量军火库后，将重新分配25亿英镑的国防预算，相当于约32亿美元，以补充弹药库存。</p><p>克里姆林宫入侵乌克兰并没有阻止英国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/news-explainers/how-british-storm-shadow-missiles-help-ukraines-counteroffensive/C0953C64-8212-4252-9D0B-CBE5C900CC49?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">——英国一直是基辅最大的政治和军事支持者之一</a>——计划将军队人数从82,000人削减至72,500人，使英国拥有自1714年以来最小的陆军部队该公司还正在积极采取行动，用 148 辆现代版挑战者坦克取代其 227 辆旧挑战者坦克。国防官员表示，乌克兰与俄罗斯的战斗表明，规模较小、装备精良的部队可以给规模更大的对手造成重大损失。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818397?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰新兵在英格兰南部的军事设施接受挑战者坦克操作训练。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：莱昂尼尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管如此，注重质量而非数量的决定凸显了资金短缺的欧洲国家在试图增强军事力量以阻止俄罗斯进一步侵略时面临的艰难选择。分析人士称，英国是北大西洋公约组织在欧洲的主要盟友之一，并且已经<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-and-allies-weigh-sending-ukraine-heavy-tanks-pointing-to-new-phase-of-the-war-11673292503?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在国防和援助乌克兰方面投入了大量资金</a>，但经过多年的预算削减，其军队已经被掏空。</p><p>乌克兰战斗造成的惨重伤亡——在一场激烈的冲突中消耗了大量的炮弹和装甲库存——也引发了分析人士和军事专家对英国专注于技术而不是规模的决定的质疑。英国议会国防委员会在本月的一份报告中得出结论：“英国目前的战斗装备储备极其有限，包括军舰、现代装甲车或战斗机。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>英国应该扩大军力还是提升军力质量？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>自 20 世纪 80 年代中期以来，军费开支占英国国内生产总值的比例已减少一半，降至 2.2% 左右。英国首相苏纳克最近表示，未来两年将增加 50 亿英镑的军费开支。这笔资金将主要用于升级核防御系统和补充交给乌克兰的武器库存。</p><p>英国政府从 2020 年开始增加国防支出，今年英国历史上首次达到 500 亿英镑，但近期的增长大部分已被通货膨胀所抵消。苏纳克表示，英国的目标是将 GDP 的 2.5% 用于国防，但前提是经济情况允许。由于预计经济增长将持续多年缓慢，政府如果想加强军队，可能不得不削减其他公共服务。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EDA02BF5-0836-4277-AB7C-10442F70192F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdespite-ukraine-war-u-k-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">拜登政府表示，计划向乌克兰发送集束弹药，以加强该国对俄罗斯军队的攻势。 《华尔街日报》解释了这些武器背后的技术以及它们为何引起人道主义担忧。插图：雅各布·亚历山大·尼尔森<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>与此同时，英国军方的高级领导层也即将进行改组。国防部长本·华莱士本周末表示，他将在今年晚些时候辞去这一职务。华莱士长期以来一直主张为军队提供更多资金，他警告说，如果没有额外的资金，英国军队将陷入困境。</p><p>英国陆军最高将领帕特里克·桑德斯 (Patrick Sanders) 在执掌两年后将于 2024 年卸任，任期比陆军许多人预期的要短。桑德斯最近在一次演讲中表示，英国不应该躲在北约盟友身后，依靠它们来弥补自己的军事缺口。华莱士否认英国在逃避责任，称英国需要一支装备精良而不仅仅是规模庞大的军队。</p><p>写信给马克斯·科尔切斯特<a href="mailto:Max.Colchester@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Max.Colchester@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 12:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-ukraine-war-uk-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-ukraine-war-uk-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424<author><![CDATA[Max Colchester]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Nuclear-Capable ‘Boomer’ Sub Visits South Korea for First Time in Decades]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>肯塔基号航母抵达港口城市釜山旨在向朝鲜发出威慑信息<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062641"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="557" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818998?width=860&amp;height=557" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国官员库尔特·坎贝尔周二在首尔表示，“我们最重视的问题莫过于我们的核威慑力量和信心。”</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：韩联社新闻/祖马出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062641"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">蒂莫西·W·马丁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日上午 7:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>首尔——一艘美国核潜艇四十多年来首次访问韩国港口，随着朝鲜<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-koreas-failed-spy-satellite-wasnt-ready-for-military-use-seoul-analysis-shows-703b0b83?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加大威胁力度</a>并承诺不断推进军事进展，这增强了威慑力。</p><p>肯塔基号潜艇是美军最大的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-its-biggest-sub-to-korean-peninsula-in-message-to-north-and-south-d998518?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">潜艇之一，被称为“婴儿潮级”潜艇</a>，于周二抵达韩国港口城市釜山。美国军舰可以无限期地保持在水下状态，并可以向数千英里外的目标发射核弹头。俄亥俄级核潜艇上一次进行此类访问是在 1981 年。</p><p>这次港口访问恰逢美国和韩国之间新的核磋商小组的首次会议。这两件事都是拜登总统和韩国总统尹锡烈于四月下旬达成的一项名为《华盛顿宣言》的协议的关键方面。</p><p>作为该协议的一部分，韩国重申其不发展自己核武器的承诺。作为回报，美国承诺向该地区派遣战略资产，例如俄亥俄级肯塔基号航空母舰和B-52轰炸机。核磋商小组的成立旨在让首尔首次在有关美国可能使用核武器应对朝鲜袭击的审议中拥有更大的发言权。</p><p> In recent days, Pyongyang has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-accuses-u-s-spy-plane-of-territorial-intrusion-422bafa3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ratcheted up its state-media vitriol</a> toward Washington and Seoul. Kim Yo Jong, the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-sister-kim-yo-jong-11607524273?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">younger sister</a> of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">Kim Jong Un</a> and a regime mouthpiece, said the tensions on the Korean Peninsula today were worse than in 2017, when former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> exchanged escalating threats with Pyongyang before the two sides pivoted toward peace talks. Last week, North Korea <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-suspected-long-range-missile-4fcd270f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">conducted a second launch</a> of its new Hwasong-18 intercontinental ballistic missile, which is suspected to have enough range to reach the US mainland. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818999?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The USS Kentucky, which arrived Tuesday in the South Korean port city of Busan, can stay submerged indefinitely and fire nuclear warheads at targets thousands of miles away.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mcs2 Amanda R. Gray/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Yoon, a conservative who took office last year, had raised concern among US officials after suggesting in January that South Korea could pursue its own nuclear weapons.</p><p> After Tuesday&#39;s meeting, Kim Tae-hyo, a senior Yoon administration national-security official, said the US extended deterrence meant that South Korea saw no need to pursue its own nuclear armament. He added that a nuclear attack from North Korea would be met with a “swift, overwhelming and decisive” response that would mean the end of the Kim Jong Un regime—echoing similar language used by Biden during Yoon&#39;s April state visit.</p><p> “There is no issue we take more seriously than the strength, than the confidence in our nuclear deterrence,” said Kurt Campbell, the Biden administration&#39;s senior Asia policy official, who helped lead the nuclear-consultative meeting that featured a contingent of roughly 30 US officials.</p><p> Campbell said the US hadn&#39;t undertaken an effort like the Nuclear Consultative Group since the early periods of the Cold War.</p><p> The USS Kentucky port visit demonstrates the “flexibility, survivability, readiness, resolve, and capability” of the US Navy&#39;s submarine forces, said US Forces Korea, which oversees the 28,500 American military personnel stationed in the country. It referred to the ballistic-missile platform as the “most survivable leg of the nuclear triad.”</p><p> North Korea has grown more belligerent than normal, taking offense over the planned US nuclear-capable submarine port visit, the Biden administration&#39;s decision to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">provide cluster munitions to Ukraine</a> and legal reconnaissance flights around the Korean Peninsula that the North claims were unlawful intrusions.</p><p> As she has done previously, Kim Yo Jong, the dictator&#39;s sister, labeled peace talks with the US or South Korea as pointless and fleeting, saying agreements are reversed by changes in administrations, state media reported Tuesday. She added that the US wouldn&#39;t be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-is-training-children-to-target-american-bastards-with-bombs-54c87a2d" target="_blank" class="icon none">able to halt North Korea&#39;s military advances</a> .</p><p> Write to Timothy W. Martin at <a href="mailto:Timothy.Martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Timothy.Martin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187<author><![CDATA[Timothy W. Martin]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>Military Watercraft</category><category> Military Submarines/Submersibles</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>Defense Equipment/Products</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>military watercraft</category><category> military submarines</category><category> submersibles</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>defense equipment</category><category>产品</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How Long Does Inflation Anger Linger? Spain May Have the Answer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Spain has brought its inflation rate down to target earlier than most, but it is taking time for voters to feel the benefit <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059456"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815605?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Frustration has lingered in Spain over the cost of food and other essentials.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Zorrakino/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059456"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-hannon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paul Hannon</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/humza-jilani" itemprop="url" rel="author">Humza Jilani</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 18, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-long-does-inflation-anger-linger-spanish-voters-may-have-the-answer-c8100cda"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Spain has had notable success in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/inflation-tracker-cpi-data-prices-11657717467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tamping down inflation</a> , but for voters, the benefits will take a while to register—probably too long to make a difference at Sunday&#39;s election.</p><p> This weekend&#39;s ballot will decide the shape of the next government. It will also be a test case for whether voters perceive that the worst of the recent inflation is fading or whether anger over the cost of living lingers.</p><p> There is a lesson here for the US, where inflation fueled discontent with Democrats during last year&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/midterm-elections-democracy-wins-2022-11670867485?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">midterm elections</a> and could play a major role in next year&#39;s presidential vote.</p><p> Spain&#39;s annual rate of inflation has tumbled this year, falling below the European Central Bank&#39;s 2% target in June. At 1.6%, it was well below the 5.5% pace of price rises recorded in the eurozone as a whole and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">3% registered in the US</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818935?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Spain&#39;s inflation rate had previously peaked at 10.7% in July 2022, while US inflation peaked at 9.1% in June of that year, and in the eurozone it reached its recent high of 10.6% in October.</p><p> After more than two decades of low inflation, voters in many Western countries are angry about the rising cost of living. During the Covid-19 pandemic, many countries used massive fiscal and monetary stimulus to prevent a long economic slump. That policy and the fallout from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Russia&#39;s war in Ukraine</a> drove up energy and food prices.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How will inflation readings affect Spain&#39;s upcoming election?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Now, political incumbents in Spain and elsewhere are finding they are getting little credit for improving data on growth and jobs because many voters are angry over the cost of living.</p><p> “Prices were the main topic of conversation between my friends and me,” said Carmen Paya, a nurse in Valencia. “Things have gotten better, but for my friends who really struggled a year ago, there is still frustration.”</p><p> It will take time for slowing inflation to begin to repair the damage done to real earnings by the surge in prices in 2021 and 2022. In the first three months of this year, Spanish workers were still earning less in real terms than at the start of 2022. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815592?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Spanish Prime Minister Pedro Sanchez during an election campaign rally in Madrid.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Paul Hanna/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815610?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An empty outdoor restaurant terrace in Seville, southern Spain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Angel Garcia/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Spain&#39;s economy has had a rocky few years. It has grown faster than those of other large European countries recently but remains smaller than it was in late 2019.</p><p> A strong rebound from the real estate and banking crisis it suffered a decade ago was derailed by the Covid-19 pandemic. International tourism, which accounts for a big share of activity, has only returned to 2019 levels over recent months. And with interest-rate rises starting to hit households&#39; vacation budgets across Europe, economists say growth is likely to slow in the coming years.</p><p> Any declaration of victory in the fight against inflation may be premature since the speed of the decline is partly due to statistical quirks. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818186?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> While household energy prices surged across Europe as Russia prepared and then carried out its February 2022 invasion of Ukraine, the rise in Spain was more immediate and larger than in many other countries. By March 2022, they were 60.3% higher than a year earlier.</p><p> That is because a large share of households—around 40%—pays electricity tariffs that are directly linked to daily moves in volatile wholesale prices. That is also the tariff that the national statistics agency uses to calculate inflation. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="750" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818187?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In June 2022, the government capped natural-gas prices. Wholesale natural-gas prices have fallen by 90% from their peak in late summer of 2022. As a result, household energy prices are now much lower than they were in June 2022. Similar base effects are likely to push inflation rates lower in the rest of Europe over the coming months, economists say.</p><p> Disregarding those big swings in energy prices, Spain&#39;s inflation rate looks pretty much like it does elsewhere in Europe. The core measure—which excludes energy and food—stood at 5.9% in June, compared with 5.4% in the eurozone as a whole, driven by services such as recreation and restaurants. And if energy prices steady and stop lowering the all-items inflation rate, the continued rise in services prices may push the core measure higher again.</p><p> Spain&#39;s labor unions and employers agreed in May on a schedule of pay rises over the coming years that reduces the threat of what European central bankers call “tit-for-tat” inflation, where businesses raise prices to maintain or increase profits, workers respond by demanding higher wages, and businesses raise their prices again.</p><p> The deal includes a 4% raise this year and 3% in each of 2024 and 2025.</p><p> “The more we all work in the same direction, the sooner the victory will come,” said Núria Mas, an economics professor at the IESE Business School. “This agreement will play an important role in keeping inflation low.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Marcus Walker contributed to this article.</em></p><p> Write to Paul Hannon at <a href="mailto:paul.hannon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">paul.hannon@wsj.com</a> and Humza Jilani at <a href="mailto:humza.jilani@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">humza.jilani@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-long-does-inflation-anger-linger-spanish-voters-may-have-the-answer-c8100cda</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-long-does-inflation-anger-linger-spanish-voters-may-have-the-answer-c8100cda<author><![CDATA[Paul HannonHumza Jilani]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Inflation Figures/Price Indices</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>inflation figures</category><category> price indices</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Sets Heat Record as John Kerry Arrives to Discuss Climate]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Temperatures in northwest exceed 120 degrees Fahrenheit in heat wave expected to last weeks <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059875"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818293?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A worker in China&#39;s capital, Beijing, which has registered temperatures above 104 degrees for 26 consecutive days.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andy Wong/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059875"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sha-hua" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sha Hua</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 18, 2023 6:27 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-heat-record-as-john-kerry-arrives-to-discuss-climate-6a35c686"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SINGAPORE—Temperatures in a Chinese village hit a searing 126 degrees Fahrenheit, the highest ever recorded in the country, on the same day that US climate envoy John Kerry arrived in Beijing to try <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-cop27-poorer-countries-secure-climate-damage-fund-without-pledging-faster-emissions-cuts-11668947145?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to revive stalled cooperation</a> on climate change between the world&#39;s two largest emitters of carbon dioxide.</p><p> The record was set on Sunday in Sanbao, a remote township outside the city of Turpan in China&#39;s northwestern Xinjiang region, according to state media. Four other townships in the Turpan Depression, a 19,000 square mile basin of sand dunes and dried up lake beds, recorded temperatures of more than 122 degrees.</p><p> Heat waves <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weeks-of-extreme-heat-strain-small-businesses-and-economy-add05101?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have been ravaging the globe</a> in recent days. More than 100 million Americans are suffering from a streak of 110-degree days <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dangerous-heat-wave-broils-southern-u-s-87f1f969?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">blanketing the South and Southwest</a> , while extreme heat <a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/heat-wave-hits-italy-spain-and-greece-temperatures-above-111-degrees/9AEFE6BB-14B5-4D45-ACBD-0E0D834E17F4.html?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is sweeping across Italy, Spain and Greece</a> . Last week was the Earth&#39;s hottest week on record, and followed the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/june-hottest-on-record-heat-b222c05c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hottest June on record</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=AEFDD20E-B8EC-4F14-B1AA-8439E0D73B67&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-sets-heat-record-as-john-kerry-arrives-to-discuss-climate-6a35c686&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Special Presidential Envoy for Climate John Kerry met with Chinese Premier Li Qiang in a visit aimed to try to revive stalled cooperation on climate change. Photo: Florence Lo/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>China is particularly vulnerable to rising temperatures as climate change accelerates, Chinese officials have warned. Annual temperatures in China rose by an average of 0.16 degrees Celsius every decade since the start of last century, faster than the global average, according to this year&#39;s Blue Book on Climate Change of China published by China&#39;s Meteorological Association this month.</p><p> Swaths of China have baked under scorching heat this summer and the current wave is expected to last until the end of the month. Many cities have turned air-raid shelters, which can be nearly 20 degrees Fahrenheit cooler than outside, into refuges for residents trying to escape the heat, state media said.</p><p> Local governments instructed people in affected areas to avoid outdoor activities and reduce their work hours if they had to work outside in the heat. Chinese media haven&#39;t reported any human deaths from this current heat wave but said more than 4,000 chickens and 462 pigs <a href="https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202307/1294140.shtml" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">perished in the heat</a> last week after power failures. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818291?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A mist machine offered relief from high temperatures in Shanghai last week.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ying Tang/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Paris Agreement set a goal of limiting global warming since the preindustrial era to well under 2 degrees Celsius and preferably to 1.5 degrees. Climate experts warn that it is increasingly likely global temperatures <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-warming-likely-to-pass-1-5-degree-threshold-in-next-five-years-u-n-report-says-a829b40b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">will breach the 1.5 degrees Celsius threshold</a> , and that mitigating the worst effects of climate change will require the US and China to work together.</p><p> Climate talks between the US and China ground to a halt after then-House Speaker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> &#39;s trip to Taiwan last summer but were revived three months later on the sidelines of the annual climate gathering in Egypt.</p><p> Kerry is expected to spend three days in Beijing in an effort to reboot climate cooperation between Beijing and Washington on several pressing issues, including the reduction of coal use and emissions of methane, a greenhouse gas that escapes during gas and oil production. The two sides are also expected to discuss technical issues to prepare the ground before the next climate summit, in Dubai at the end of the year.</p><p> Kerry spent four hours on Monday meeting with his Chinese counterpart Xie Zhenhua in the Beijing Hotel near the Forbidden City, according to state broadcaster China Central Television. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818292?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Visitors coped with the heat on a visit to the Forbidden City in Beijing this month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: greg baker/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> China has been combating extreme weather all year. In January, a city in northeastern China saw temperatures plummet as low as minus 63 degrees Fahrenheit. Heavy rains devastated wheat fields in central China in May and Beijing, the capital, has been facing one of its hottest summers on record, with temperatures soaring past 104 degrees for 26 consecutive days.</p><p> Some experts say this year&#39;s heat waves might stem in part from El Niño, a hard-to-predict climate pattern caused by warming of ocean surface temperatures in the Pacific Ocean, which could lead to a surge in global temperatures and disruptive weather and climate patterns.</p><p> Last year, scorching heat and record-low rainfall in August <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-scorching-heat-and-hydropower-missteps-test-nations-power-grid-11661514473?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">led to power shortages in China</a> , which damaged crop yields, forced offices to shut down and led to the temporary suspension of plant operations for Toyota, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/VOW" class="company-name">Volkswagen</a> and some suppliers for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> supplier</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TW/XTAI/2317" class="">Foxconn</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span><p></p><p> Write to Sha Hua at <a href="mailto:sha.hua@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sha.hua@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 10:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-heat-record-as-john-kerry-arrives-to-discuss-climate-6a35c686</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-heat-record-as-john-kerry-arrives-to-discuss-climate-6a35c686<author><![CDATA[Sha Hua]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Climate Change</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>Global/World Issues</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Weather</category><category> Routine Weather Reports</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>约翰·克里</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>global</category><category> world issues</category><category>政治</category><category>weather</category><category> routine weather reports</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Man Charged With Steering the Yuan Through China’s Economic Turmoil]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Pan Gongsheng has experience in high-stakes tasks, but China&#39;s fragile economy raises new risks <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818268/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Pan Gongsheng has been given some room to help shape yuan policy." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Pan Gongsheng has been given some room to help shape yuan policy. Andy Wong/Associated Press <span>Andy Wong/Associated Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059311"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059311"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lingling-wei" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lingling Wei</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">Stella Yifan Xie</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jason Douglas</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 18, 2023 12:02 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> A veteran economist and banker had been getting ready to retire in the weeks before Chinese leader Xi Jinping picked him to lead China&#39;s central bank, according to officials familiar with the matter.</p><p> Now, Pan Gongsheng is set to take the reins at the People&#39;s Bank of China as it confronts an urgent challenge: whether and how to defend the Chinese yuan.</p><p> The Chinese currency&#39;s value <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yuan-under-pressure-as-u-s-china-rates-set-to-diverge-further-aa655bcd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">has been sliding</a> this year, as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=hp_lead_pos1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">the world&#39;s second-largest economy stagnates</a> . Economists and some Beijing officials worry the decline could turn into a rout, destabilizing China&#39;s financial system.</p><p> But propping up the currency brings its own risks, including slower growth for China and, potentially, the rest of the world, economists say.</p><p> Xi elevated Pan, the 60-year-old, Western-trained deputy PBOC governor of the past decade, because of his reputation as an experienced technocrat who could <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-plans-to-appoint-a-new-central-bank-governor-56a878ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">work well with foreign officials</a> , The Wall Street Journal has reported.</p><p> For now, Xi and his new leadership team have given little indication of Beijing&#39;s preferences, giving the new PBOC chief some room to help shape the yuan policy.</p><p> In Pan, Xi picked a man with a history of handling high-stakes tasks with global implications. But Pan has zigzagged over the years as a policy maker, depending on the top leadership&#39;s priorities.</p><p> During the early years of Xi&#39;s rule, which started in 2012, Pan promoted financial liberalization as part of the leader&#39;s agenda to give market forces bigger sway over the economy. That sometimes led to a freer—but weaker—yuan.</p><p> Other times, when there were sharp declines in the yuan&#39;s value, Pan advocated harsh capital controls to suit the leadership&#39;s demand to keep the currency stable, even as that contributed to weaker growth.</p><p> “Pan will be tested right out of the gate in establishing his credentials as a reformer committed to a more market-determined exchange rate,” said Eswar Prasad, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution and former China head for the International Monetary Fund.</p><h3> Yuan Under Pressure </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818270?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The yuan&#39;s value has been falling this year and downward pressure is expected to continue.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cfoto/ZUMA Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Over the past six months, the yuan has fallen more than 6% against the dollar. At one point in late June, one dollar was valued at around 7.2 yuan, a level close to the weakest point since the 2008 global financial crisis.</p><p> In recent days, the PBOC has signaled—mainly through the official rate it sets to guide the yuan&#39;s daily trading—that its tolerance for fast depreciation <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-weakening-currency-is-becoming-a-headache-for-its-central-bank-372ec31d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">might be wearing thin</a> . The yuan has rebounded to 7.17 against the dollar.</p><p> Downward pressure on the yuan is expected to persist, however. One big reason is that the PBOC is expected to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-cuts-borrowing-rates-again-in-bid-to-juice-recovery-466b1d90?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">keep cutting interest rates</a> to support growth, while its counterparts in the West will likely raise rates further to fight inflation. That East-West rate gap encourages investors to move money out of China, depressing the yuan. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818950?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Any potential weakness in the dollar in the coming months, analysts said, is unlikely to change the yuan&#39;s downward trajectory without government intervention and a robust recovery in China&#39;s growth.</p><p> “If the PBOC doesn&#39;t put up any visible resistance, the most likely future direction of the yuan is down,” said Brad Setser, a China currency and debt expert at the US Council on Foreign Relations. China has built a sizable war chest to defend the yuan if it chooses to, including about $3 trillion in foreign-exchange reserves.</p><p> Xi, the third-term Chinese leader whose power rivals that of Mao Zedong, has made it clear that he has the final say on all major decisions including those involving the economy.</p><p> But he still seeks policy recommendations, especially for wonky issues such as currency management. He is expected to do so with Pan, who is set to be named PBOC governor in addition to his new role as the top Communist Party official at the bank.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think China&#39;s economy will stabilize this year? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> US Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen met with Pan <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/janet-yellen-says-u-s-china-making-progress-on-managing-economic-tensions-1e2c07?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">during her trip to Beijing</a> early this month and discussed China&#39;s currency management with him, according to people with knowledge of the matter. Treasury officials have been seeking more information about how Beijing manages its currency, and the department has long criticized China for not being more transparent about its currency practices.</p><p> Part of the challenge now for Beijing is that China&#39;s economy is in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-fading-recovery-reveals-deeper-economic-struggles-31f4097b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">worse shape than years past</a> , constraining the central bank&#39;s room to maneuver.</p><p> If it takes a more hands-off approach and lets the market guide the yuan lower, that would likely help China&#39;s economy by boosting exports. But it would also risk a spiral of currency depreciation and capital outflows that could threaten China&#39;s stability, rippling through global markets.</p><p> More aggressive intervention to defend the yuan, however, would make China&#39;s exports less competitive. It would also make it harder for the PBOC to keep cutting interest rates, hurting China&#39;s—and the world&#39;s—growth.</p><p> Some analysts expect Pan to take a more interventionist approach to slow the yuan&#39;s depreciation in the short run. That could win him some political capital with the leadership, which seems to be obsessed with economic stability.</p><p> Then, those analysts say, Pan could use the political capital to push for a more market-driven yuan as he and his predecessors had advocated before.</p><h3> China&#39;s &#39;Hotel California&#39; </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="423" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818279?width=700&amp;height=423" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Pan Gongsheng in previous years zigzagged as a policy maker, depending on the top leadership&#39;s priorities.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Felix Wong/South China Morning Post/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Trained in economics at Chinese universities, Pan did postdoctoral research at Cambridge University in the late 1990s and spent a few months at Harvard University in 2011 as a research fellow.</p><p> His career took off in the 2000s after he led efforts to restructure and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704545004575352690672090642?mc_cid=480b08d787&amp;mc_eid=057b96de38&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">take public in the US</a> two of China&#39;s biggest state-owned banks. Pan joined the central bank in 2012 as a deputy governor and pushed for making China&#39;s yuan and the overall financial sector more market-oriented.</p><p> In 2016, soon after he was named China&#39;s top foreign-exchange regulator, part of the central bank, Pan convinced top leaders to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-issuing-strict-controls-on-overseas-investment-1480071529?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">slap strict restrictions</a> on Chinese companies&#39; investing overseas in a bid to fight capital flight. Chinese outflows were weakening the yuan, forcing the central bank to spend $1 trillion, or a quarter of its currency reserves at the time, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-crusade-to-prop-up-yuan-neglects-other-pressing-needs-1492107144?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to arrest the yuan&#39;s fall</a> .</p><p> That was followed by more regulatory barriers to keep money from leaving China, essentially dialing back years of efforts—including some championed by Pan—to make it easier for the Chinese to invest overseas and more attractive for foreigners to invest in China.</p><p> Some foreign investors since then have dubbed China “Hotel California,” where investors can check out but never leave. Still, Pan was praised by foreign investors for seeking them out to explain the central-bank&#39;s policy.</p><p> Shortly after the capital-control moves in late 2016, he attended a forum organized by the European Chamber of Commerce in China and told the audience that the central bank&#39;s paramount goal at the time was to “safeguard the stability” of China&#39;s foreign-exchange market.</p><p> In 2018, as China&#39;s currency came under pressure again, he famously warned traders from betting against the yuan.</p><p> An alternate member of the party&#39;s 205-member Central Committee since 2017, Pan wasn&#39;t named a full member at the most recent party Congress, suggesting he had been passed over for promotion.</p><p> But Xi turned to Pan for the PBOC job on broad support within the nation&#39;s economic hierarchy for his technocratic know-how, from people such as Liu He, a longtime economic adviser to Xi, and central-bank veterans including former PBOC Gov. Zhou Xiaochuan and the current governor, Yi Gang, officials familiar with the matter said.</p><p> “Pan&#39;s elevation is a choice of policy continuity and technocratic know-how, which in the context of China&#39;s economic challenges and political dynamics should be considered reassuring,” said Michael Hirson, head of China Research at New York-based consulting firm 22V Research and a former US Treasury officer.</p><p> — <em>Grace Zhu contributed to this article.</em></p><p> Write to Lingling Wei at <a href="mailto:Lingling.Wei@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lingling.Wei@wsj.com</a> , Stella Yifan Xie at <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a> and Jason Douglas at <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 04:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8<author><![CDATA[Lingling WeiStella Yifan XieJason Douglas]]></author><category> Central Banking</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Monetary Policy</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Money/Currency Markets</category><category> Commodity/Financial Market News</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Pan Gongsheng</category><category> monetary policy</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>money</category><category> currency markets</category><category> commodity</category><category> financial market news</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>central banking</category><category> financial services</category></item></channel></rss>